{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JUj1ehQTKYuDdBVqMRSDrM","type":"tool_result","content":"165\t\n166\t    All units must be in the canonical format produced by\n167\t    ``definitions.cases.normalize_precondition_units``. No format\n168\t    detection or legacy field handling is performed here; the legacy\n169\t    execution branch from ``run_flow.py`` is not carried forward.\n170\t\n171\t    For each unit, the probe tests whether the target state already holds:\n172\t\n173\t    * probe **passes** -> state already present, apply is skipped.\n174\t    * probe **fails** + ``on_probe_fail=\"skip\"`` (the default, used by setup\n175\t      units) -> the \"not yet present\" signal is expected, so apply runs to\n176\t      establish the state, then verify.\n177\t    * probe **fails** + ``on_probe_fail=\"error\"`` -> a readiness/convergence\n178\t      gate the apply cannot satisfy. The probe is retried up to\n179\t      ``verify_retries`` times (``verify_interval_sec`` apart) to let a slow\n180\t      cluster converge; the failure becomes fatal only after that budget.\n181\t\n182\t    Retries verify up to ``verify_retries`` times with\n183\t    ``verify_interval_sec`` between attempts. All command output is\n184\t    appended to *log_path*.\n185\t\n186\t    ``phase_timeout_sec`` bounds the wall-clock time of the whole phase\n187\t    (``None`` = unbounded, the default for callers that do not opt in).\n188\t    When set, each command's timeout is capped to the remaining budget and\n189\t    the phase aborts as soon as the deadline passes -- this is what makes\n190\t    ``--setup-timeout`` (``settings.precondition_timeout_sec``) actually\n191\t    bound the precondition phase, mirroring the oracle's wall-clock cap.\n192\t\n193\t    Returns\n194\t    -------\n195\t    dict\n196\t        Keys: ``ok`` (bool), ``units`` (list[dict] of per-unit outcomes),\n197\t        ``output`` (str), ``timed_out`` (bool -- True if the phase budget\n198\t        was exhausted).\n199\t    \"\"\"\n200\t    import os\n201\t    import subprocess\n202\t\n203\t    log_path.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\n204\t    env = {**os.environ, **role_bindings, **(env_vars or {})}\n205\t    all_output: list[str] = []\n206\t    unit_outcomes: list[dict[str, Any]] = []\n207\t    overall_ok = True\n208\t\n209\t    # Wall-clock deadline for the whole phase. ``None`` means unbounded.\n210\t    deadline = (time.monotonic() + phase_timeout_sec) if phase_timeout_sec else None\n211\t    timed_out = False\n212\t\n213\t    def _exec(cmd_entry: dict[str, Any], phase: str, unit_id: str):\n214\t        \"\"\"Run one command, capping its timeout to the remaining phase budget.\n215\t\n216\t        Returns the subprocess return code, or ``None`` if the command did\n217\t        not complete (error or timeout). A timeout that occurs once the phase\n218\t        budget is the binding constraint sets the enclosing ``timed_out`` flag.\n219\t        \"\"\"\n220\t        nonlocal timed_out\n221\t        cmd = cmd_entry[\"command\"]\n222\t        # Explicit timeout_sec wins; otherwise infer from the command verb\n223\t        # (wait/rollout get minutes) instead of the flat command_timeout_sec.\n224\t        base_to = cmd_entry.get(\"timeout_sec\") or _default_timeout_for_command(cmd, phase)\n225\t        cmd_to = base_to\n226\t        capped = False  # True once the phase budget is the binding constraint.\n227\t        if deadline is not None:\n228\t            remaining = deadline - time.monotonic()\n229\t            if remaining <= 0:\n230\t                timed_out = True\n231\t                marker = \"[setup timeout: phase budget exhausted]\"\n232\t                all_output.append(f\"$ {cmd}\\n{marker}\\n\")\n233\t                with log_path.open(\"a\") as fh:\n234\t                    fh.write(f\"[{label}:{unit_id}:{phase}] $ {cmd}\\n{marker}\\n\")\n235\t                return None\n236\t            cmd_to = max(1, min(base_to, int(remaining)))\n237\t            capped = cmd_to < base_to\n238\t        try:\n239\t            proc = subprocess.run(\n240\t                cmd, shell=True, capture_output=True, text=True, env=env, timeout=cmd_to\n241\t            )\n242\t            out = proc.stdout + proc.stderr\n243\t            all_output.append(f\"$ {cmd}\\n{out}\")\n244\t            with log_path.open(\"a\") as fh:\n245\t                fh.write(f\"[{label}:{unit_id}:{phase}] $ {cmd}\\n{out}\\n\")\n246\t            if cmd_entry.get(\"sleep\"):\n247\t                time.sleep(cmd_entry[\"sleep\"])\n248\t            return proc.returncode\n249\t        except subprocess.TimeoutExpired:\n250\t            # A timeout while the budget was capping this command (or the\n251\t            # deadline has since passed) is a phase timeout; a timeout at the\n252\t            # command's own declared limit is an ordinary command failure.\n253\t            if capped or (deadline is not None and time.monotonic() >= deadline):\n254\t                timed_out = True\n255\t                marker = f\"[setup timeout after {cmd_to}s]\"\n256\t            else:\n257\t                marker = f\"[timed out after {cmd_to}s]\"\n258\t            all_output.append(f\"$ {cmd}\\n{marker}\\n\")\n259\t            with log_path.open(\"a\") as fh:\n260\t                fh.write(f\"[{label}:{unit_id}:{phase}] $ {cmd}\\n{marker}\\n\")\n261\t            return None\n262\t        except Exception as exc:\n263\t            all_output.append(f\"$ {cmd}\\n[error: {exc}]\\n\")\n264\t            with log_path.open(\"a\") as fh:\n265\t                fh.write(f\"[{label}:{unit_id}:{phase}] $ {cmd}\\n[error: {exc}]\\n\")\n266\t            return None\n267\t\n268\t    for unit in units or []:\n269\t        if timed_out:\n270\t            break\n271\t        unit_id = unit.get(\"id\") or unit.get(\"name\") or \"unknown\"\n272\t        on_fail = unit.get(\"on_probe_fail\", \"skip\")\n273\t        if on_progress:\n274\t            on_progress(f\"    • {label}: {unit_id}\")\n275\t\n276\t        # Probe. A skip-gate probes once: a failure just means \"not present\n277\t        # yet\" -> fall through to apply. An error-gate asserts a state the apply\n278\t        # cannot create (a readiness/convergence condition: pods Ready, cluster\n279\t        # quorate, a planted baseline reaching its expected steady-state). On a\n280\t        # loaded/slow cluster a one-shot check is flaky and such a condition may\n281\t        # need a few seconds to settle, so an error-gate retries its probe up to\n282\t        # verify_retries times with verify_interval_sec between tries before the\n283\t        # failure becomes fatal. This never turns a genuine miss into a pass --\n284\t        # if the state never holds it still fails after the budget; it only"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"59a38707-920e-4a31-95ed-9d14553d1308","uuid":"93a5b642-84a0-43f3-8044-66c3f440c869","timestamp":"2026-07-03T13:22:21.051Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/mydata/karma/karma/runtime/case.py","content":"\n    All units must be in the canonical format produced by\n    ``definitions.cases.normalize_precondition_units``. No format\n    detection or legacy field handling is performed here; the legacy\n    execution branch from ``run_flow.py`` is not carried forward.\n\n    For each unit, the probe tests whether the target state already holds:\n\n    * probe **passes** -> state already present, apply is skipped.\n    * probe **fails** + ``on_probe_fail=\"skip\"`` (the default, used by setup\n      units) -> the \"not yet present\" signal is expected, so apply runs to\n      establish the state, then verify.\n    * probe **fails** + ``on_probe_fail=\"error\"`` -> a readiness/convergence\n      gate the apply cannot satisfy. The probe is retried up to\n      ``verify_retries`` times (``verify_interval_sec`` apart) to let a slow\n      cluster converge; the failure becomes fatal only after that budget.\n\n    Ret